<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
Delicate, moderately large otoliths reaching up to 3.2 mm length (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. A-C: Diogenichthys aguilerai Schwarzhans, 2013, SMF PO 101.112, Tsuyama City, Takakura Formation, level MS 04.5; D-L: Myctophum murbani (Weinfurter, 1952); D-I, K-L; SMF PO 101.113, Tsuyama City, Takakura Formation, levels MS 15, MS 27, MS 52, h, J) SMF PO 101.114 Mizunami City, Oidawara Formation; M-O: Myctophum sp., col. Tsuchiya, Ichishi Group; P-Z: Protomyctophum ahunga Schwarzhans, 2019, SMF PO 101.115, Tsuyama City, Takakura Formation, levels MS 15, MS 22, MS 36, h." figureDoi="10.3897/zitteliana.96.83571.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/694118" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">5H</figureCitation>
). OL:OH = 1.15-1.25; OH:OT = 4.0-4.3. Ventral rim well rounded, deep, very regularly curved; dorsal rim much shallower, likewise regularly curved, sometimes with very mild obliquely cut postdorsal section. Rostrum and antirostrum short, of equal length, with very small excisura in between; posterior rim regularly curved. Rostral tip and posterior tip positioned at lower margin of sulcus and distinctly supramedian. All rims delicately crenulated, ventral rim usually more intensely than dorsal rim.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Inner face distinctly convex, smooth, with distinctly supramedian, long, narrow sulcus. OL:SuL = 1.2; OCL:CCL = 1.9-2.5. Dorsal margin of ostium slightly oscillating; cauda slightly bent upwards, with angular upper-posterior termination. Caudal colliculum narrower than ostial colliculum but of equal width when incorporating underlying pseudocolliculum. Dorsal depression shallow, indistinct; ventral furrow indistinct, far from ventral rim of otolith. Outer face flat to slightly convex, less than inner face, with short radial furrows near rims and smooth central portion.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Weinfurter" baseAuthorityYear="1952" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Myctophum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myctophum murbani" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="murbani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Myctophum murbani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to a group of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Myctophum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myctophum" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Myctophum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with oval otoliths that usually also show a strong marginal ornamentation. This group contains the extant species 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. lychnobium" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="lychnobium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">M. lychnobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bolin, 1946, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. obtusirostre" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="obtusirostre">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">M. obtusirostre</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Tåning">Taning</normalizedToken>
, 1928, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. orientale" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="orientale">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">M. orientale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Gilbert, 1913), and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. spinosum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="spinosum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">M. spinosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Steindachner, 1867) (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Ohe, F" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Senior High School attached to the Aichi University of Education" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" refId="B47" refString="Ohe, F, 1985. Marine fish otoliths of Japan. The senior high school attached to the Aichi University of Education, special volume of Bulletin (Earth Science): 1-184." title="Marine fish otoliths of Japan. The senior high school attached to the Aichi University of Education, special volume of Bulletin (Earth Science): 1 - 184." year="1985">Ohe 1985</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Palaeo Ichthyologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="83 - 150" refId="B61" refString="Schwarzhans, W, Aguilera, OA, 2013. Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America. Palaeo Ichthyologica 13: 83 - 150" title="Otoliths of the Myctophidae from the Neogene of tropical America." volume="13" year="2013">Schwarzhans and Aguilera 2013</bibRefCitation>
for figures). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Weinfurter" baseAuthorityYear="1952" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Myctophum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myctophum murbani" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="murbani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Myctophum murbani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only fossil representative of this group and differs from all of them in the more gently curving ventral rim (vs. pronounced mid-ventral angle or expansion) and the more regularly curved dorsal rim. In addition, the postdorsal termination of the cauda is less strongly bent upwards and at a less sharp angle than in the extant species. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Weinfurter" baseAuthorityYear="1952" class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Myctophum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myctophum murbani" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="murbani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Myctophum murbani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Weinfurter, 1952) is a widely distributed tropical to subtropical species that occurred in the late Burdigalian to Langhian in the Caribbean, the Mediterranean, the Paratethys, and now also in Japan. Thus far, no coeval 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Myctophidae" genus="Myctophum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myctophum" order="Myctophiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Myctophum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
otoliths are known from the southern hemisphere (i.e., New Zealand or Chile; see 
<bibRefCitation author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Memorie Della Societa Italiana Di Scienze Naturali e Del Museon Di Storia Naturale Di Milano" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="3 - 326" refId="B60" refString="Schwarzhans, W, 2019. Reconstruction of the fossil marine bony fish fauna (Teleostei) from the Eocene to Pleistocene of New Zealand by means of otoliths. Memorie Della Societa Italiana Di Scienze Naturali e Del Museon Di Storia Naturale Di Milano 46: 3 - 326" title="Reconstruction of the fossil marine bony fish fauna (Teleostei) from the Eocene to Pleistocene of New Zealand by means of otoliths." volume="46" year="2019">Schwarzhans 2019</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1186/s13358-021-00228-w" author="Schwarzhans, WW" journalOrPublisher="Paleobiology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" refId="B63" refString="Schwarzhans, WW, Nielsen, SN, 2021. Fish otoliths from the early Miocene of Chile: a window into the evolution of marine bony fishes in the Southeast Pacific. Swiss Journal of Palaeontology 140: e16. [62 pp] https://doi.org/10.1186/s13358-021-00228-w" title="Fish otoliths from the early Miocene of Chile: a window into the evolution of marine bony fishes in the Southeast Pacific. Swiss Journal of Palaeontology 140: e 16. [62 pp]" url="https://doi.org/10.1186/s13358-021-00228-w" year="2021">Schwarzhans and Nielsen 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
